Joonas Kokkonen (pronounced [ˈjoːnɑs ˈkokːonen] (listen); 13 November 1921 – 2 October 1996) was a Finnish composer.

He was one of the most internationally famous Finnish composers of the 20th century after Sibelius; his opera The Last Temptations has received over 500 performances worldwide, and is considered by many to be Finland's most distinguished national opera.

Usually his compositions are divided into three style periods: a neo-classical early style from 1948 to 1958, a relatively short middle period twelve-tone style from 1959 to 1966, and a late "neo-Romantic" style of free tonality which also used aspects of his earlier style periods, which began in 1967 and lasted for the rest of his life.

In the second style period he wrote the first two of his four symphonies.
